cium channels","ATP-dependent calcium pumping","Sodium-calcium exchange","Passive diffusion through membrane pores"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECalcium-induced calcium release through ryanodine receptors\u003C/strong\u003E is the key mechanism that triggers cardiac muscle contraction. When an action potential opens voltage-gated L-type calcium channels in the cell membrane, the initial calcium entry triggers a much larger release of calcium from the sarcoplasmic reticulum through ryanodine receptors. This amplification process provides sufficient calcium to initiate contraction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect mechanical opening of calcium channels\u003C/strong\u003E - Calcium channels are opened by voltage changes or ligand binding, not mechanical forces\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPassive diffusion through membrane pores\u003C/strong\u003E - Calcium movement is tightly regulated through specific channels and transporters\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EATP-dependent calcium pumping\u003C/strong\u003E - This process removes calcium from the cytoplasm to end contraction rather than initiating it\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESodium-calcium exchange\u003C/strong\u003E - This mechanism primarily helps remove calcium from the cell rather than triggering release\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe large release of calcium from internal stores is essential because the amount of calcium entering through membrane channels alone would be insufficient to activate the contractile machinery.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Calcium release from the sarcoplasmic reticulum through ryanodine receptors is essential for cardiac muscle contraction.","Voltage-gated L-type calcium channels in the cell membrane open during cardiac action potentials to trigger calcium-induced calcium release.","The process of calcium-induced calcium release amplifies the initial calcium signal to achieve sufficient cytoplasmic calcium for contraction."],"references":["Boron W. F., Boulpaep E. L. Medical Physiology. (3rd edition). US. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2017.","Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53423"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16954"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53423","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53423"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-08T12:15:19+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-08T12:16:00+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9644"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67958"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relati